{"questionId":"19750","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A <strong>Gaussian integer</strong> is a complex number, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mtext>i</mtext></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi></math>. In this question, you are asked to investigate certain divisibility properties of Gaussian integers.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider two Gaussian integers,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>β</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>, such that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi></math>&nbsp;for some Gaussian integer&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Now consider two Gaussian integers,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The norm of a complex number <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>, denoted by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced></math>, is defined by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. For example, if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math> then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A <strong>Gaussian prime</strong> is a Gaussian integer, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>, that <strong>cannot</strong> be expressed in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>β</mi></math> are Gaussian integers with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>β</mi></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The positive integer <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> is a prime number, however it is not a Gaussian prime.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>β</mi></math> be Gaussian integers.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The result from part (h) provides a way of determining whether a Gaussian integer is a Gaussian prime.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math> is a Gaussian prime.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></math>&nbsp;which is a prime (in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi></math>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>if&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext><mo>=</mo><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi></math>&nbsp;then&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>17</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>β</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>we cannot have&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>β</mi></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>R1</strong></em> for stating that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math> is not the product of Gaussian integers of smaller norm because no such norms divide <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>17</mn></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>&nbsp;is a Gaussian prime&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19750","referenceCode":"EXN.3.AHL.TZ0.2i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence show that 1+4i is a Gaussian prime.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}